==Old English==
===Etymology 1===
From Germanic *''war-''.  Cognate with Old High German ''[[giwar]]''.

====Pronunciation====
{{IPA|/wær/}}

====Adjective====
'''wær'''

# [[aware]], [[cautious]]

===Etymology 2===
From Germanic ''*wēra-'' ‘true’, from Indo-European ''*wēr-''.  Germanic cognates include Old High German ''[[war|wār]]'', ''[[wara|wāra]]'' (German ''[[wahr]]''), Old Saxon ''[[war|wār]]'' (Dutch ''[[waar]]''), Old Norse ''[[várar]]'' (''plural'').  The IE root is also the source of Latin ''[[verus|vērus]]'', Old Irish ''[[fír]]'' (Welsh ''[[cywir]]''), Old Church Slavonic ''[[вѣра]]'' (Russian ''[[вера]]'').

====Pronunciation====
{{IPA|/wæ:r/}}

====Adjective====
{{Latinx|'''wǣr'''}}

# [[true]] (''only attested once'')

====Noun====
{{Latinx|'''wǣr'''}} {{f}} (plural '''[[wæra|wǣra]]''' or '''[[wære|wǣre]]''')

# [[truth]], [[faith]]
# [[fidelity]], [[friendship]]
# [[agreement]], [[promise]]

